🇲🇪On the market with @montenegro.sothebysrealty, this coastal villa was named one of @mansionglobal’s top properties in 2020! Listed for €7M with @nikolakovic. The seafront villa is set at the tip of its own private peninsula near Rezevici, a short drive away from the coastal town of Petrovac where the Romans once built their coastal villas along the Adriatic Sea. The centuries-old stone villa boasts an exclusive setting on the coast of Montenegro, offering total privacy under the shade of ancient pine trees, with cypress and wild fig trees, and stunning coastal views. There are 7 beautiful terraces which surround the terracotta-roofed home, allowing you to make the most of the Mediterranean climate, with stairs carved into the cliffside, one set leading down to the beach, and another down to a private pier at the side of the peninsula where you can moor your yacht. The property offers 2152 square feet of interior space, with 2 bedrooms and 3 bathrooms in the main residence, and an additional 2 bedrooms and 2 bathrooms built into the peninsula rock. There is also a caretaker’s residence by the peninsula’s entrance. The entire property has been fully renovated and updated to a modern standard for contemporary living, while highlighting original rustic features, seen in the stone walls and wood accents throughout. It’s proximity to the renowned @amansvetistefan resort, and the future home of the Fairmont / Raffles mixed-use resort, the property is one of the most exclusive listings on this elite corner of the Adriatic! Follow @montenegro.sothebysrealty for more luxury listings. Find the listing link and more photos on the blog! .

🇫🇷Set on the French Riviera in the Cannes hillside, Villa Blanche is on the market with @vingtparis @vingtparisfrenchriviera for €19M. The lovely property has 5 separate maisons for a total of 12 bedrooms and 12 bathrooms with over 10,763 square feet of interior space. The estate was built at the beginning of the 1950s for the Polish-American beauty mogul, Helena Rubinstein. Rubinstein was the first woman to become a self-made millionaire from her global cosmetics company. (Read her fascinating history on the blog!) She commissioned French architect and co-Founder of the Compagnie des arts français, Louis Süe to build her French Riviera estate, set on a charming 2.47 acre lot in the hillside surrounded by Florentine cypresses and lush, Mediterranean greenery. Villa Blanche was recently updated by interior designer Bert Quadvlieg, and the beautiful terraced gardens were also revived under the supervision of the legendary Riviera landscape architect, Jean Mus, "the man with 1500 gardens''. A heated swimming pool is located on the west corner of the park, with a landscaped terrace. The property also offers an organic olive oil production. Maison Blanche, the main 6458 square foot residence, offers 5 bedrooms and 5 bathrooms. Maison des Amis is a 1237 square foot 2-bedroom, 2-bathroom guest house. Maison Lupatelli offers 3 bedrooms and 3 bathrooms in a 1076 square foot dwelling, and Maison de l’Artistes offers a 1-bedroom, 1-bathroom suite. There is also an additional 753 square foot one-bedroom Caretaker’s cottage on the property, with a 6 car garage beneath the cottage. Villa Blanche offers a unique opportunity to own a classic Riviera property with luxurious amenities, offering the best of the Mediterranean climate at ~1000 feet above sea level. The property is well positioned, close to the medieval village of Grasse and just 15 km from Cannes and the beautiful beaches of the Cote d’Azur.
Find more photos and the listing link on the blog!

Villa Peduzzi is one of those dreamy and ultra-luxurious vacation properties on Lake Como that will have your friends asking “Hey, how did you find this place?” Available for rent as a luxury retreat with Cameron Avery of @prestigepropertiesitaly the 9-bedroom villa comes fully equipped with a chef team, villa manager, and housekeeping. The Liberty-style villa was built in 1909 as an idyllic retreat for the Peduzzi family, an Italian engineering dynasty, and was fully reimagined in 2016 under @studiodaminato, a Singapore-based firm. It is hard not to feel like you’re floating in a dream when you stay at Villa Peduzzi, with its wide blue lake and green mountain vistas from its vantage point, 881 metres above the lake. The south-facing property has multiple terraces, an infinity pool with pool house, and a yoga room carved into the cliffside, high above the Western shores of Lake Como. And if you ever do need to come back down to earth, a cable car down to the village of Argegno is just 500 metres from the villa gates, where you’ll find the villa’s Axopar Brabus boat moored at the base of the funicular, ready to take you anywhere on the Italian lake. With many luxury retreats already booking through 2021, don’t miss your chance to experience Lake Como at Villa Peduzzi. Email cameron@prestigeproperties.it for more information and availability! It may be hard for you to believe that this English Tudor Estate is located in Pennsylvania. 🤯Guildford Manor was built in 1925, although parts of it date as far back as the 12th century, such as the great stone slab floors, from a Priory near London.
It was built by George Elkins, who had inherited his father's vast fortune created in railways, oil, gas and tobacco. In 1915, George took a trip to England where he visited his friend, the Duke of Sutherland at Sutton Place in Surrey. His time at the estate inspired him so much that he decided to build his own Tudor estate modelled after Sutton Place back home in Wyndmoor, Pennsylvania. The town is located just half an hour from Central Philadelphia and 90 minutes drive from Manhattan. 
The property took over 10 years to complete, importing architectural elements from estates in England to be incorporated into Guildford Manor, named after the town where Sutton Place is located. 
Robert McGoodwin, a protégé of the Gilded Age architect Horace Trumbauer, was hired to oversee the construction of the property. The substructure was built of reinforced concrete meant to stand for hundreds of years with the imported architectural components reassembled on site. 
The living room dates from the 15th century, taken from Cassiobury Hall, where Elizabeth I is said to have visited, marked by a stained glass window bearing her Tudor Rose emblem. (If you’re interested in more specifics, be sure to check out the listing link for an room-by-room description of the property’s British origins.) Much like Sutton Place, Guildford Manor was built for lavish living and entertaining, with a large entry hall, grand reception room, and an intimate paneled library perfect for fireside chats. 
Set on a private parklank of 18 acres, the scenic property has woodland trails, terraced gardens, a landscaped amphitheatre, and pool. The 7-bedroom, 7+5 bath home has been completely updated for 21st century living with amenities like elevators, 13 wood burning fireplaces, a 4-car garage, a wine cellar, and spa.

Listed for $8,900,000 by @franz_j_rabauer of @kurfiss_sir @sothebysrealty

node.text: 🇫🇷A dreamy 15th century stone bastide in the Luberon is on the market for €8.2M, listed with @danielfeauimmobilier. The 17 acre French country estate is set in the heart of the Luberon Natural Park, near the villages of Apt, Bonnieux and Lacoste. The stone bastide property benefits from an elevated positioning which showcases stunning views of the surrounding Luberon hills. Surrounded by lovely gardens and elegant terraces with old fountains, the property’s lush grounds contain centennial oak trees, cypresses, and olive trees, evoking a type of French country romance you can only find in the south of France. With a swimming pool, summer kitchen, and countless dreamy terraces, la vie est belle. The stone bastide spans 7319 square feet, with 6 ensuite bedrooms, some of which open out directly to the terraces overlooking the surrounding countryside. Restored in recent years, the exceptional property consists of a 3-storey stone bastide and an annex, connected through the inner courtyard. Several lovely reception rooms provide ample space for living and entertaining, and the property comes with a separate caretaker’s lodge. 🇨🇿 Chateau Žinkovy, a fairytale castle in the Czech Republic, is on the market for €26.5M, listed with @svobodawilliams. The castle is nestled in 47 acres within the Plzeň region, known for its spa towns, Bohemian forests, and mountains, set at the gateway to the European Union. Originally a fortress in the 12th century, the property was rebuilt into a castle by the 15th century under the lords of Klenová. The chateau was later owned by Prince Lobkowitz, Count Jan Nepomuk Harrach, and the knights of Wesselý who are responsible for the addition of the striking Neo-Renaissance facade by Viennese architects Fellner and Helmer. The castle was privately owned by the Škoda family until the end of WWII when it was taken over by the state and run as a rehabilitation centre by the Communist Revolutionary Trade Union Movement. Declared a cultural monument in 1963, Chateau Žinkovy was purchased privately in 1999 and gradually restored over the years. Today, the unique property is considered one-of-a-kind and at 129,167 square feet, it is the largest privately owned castle in the Czech Republic. The romantic castle has everything you could dream of: expansive wings, soaring towers, and incredible period detail, inside and out. The courtyard provides a dramatic entrance to the romantic castle, with its balconies and covered walkways. Inside, find hardwood parquet floors and countless rooms featuring frescoed ceilings and walls. Set in a charming landscape with woodland and ponds, the estate comes with several castle ruins and another castle, listed as a cultural moment, in the deep forests. A beautiful setting for weddings and celebrations (there’s even a private chapel!), the estate comes with an office, restaurant, reception and conference room, additional accommodations, as well as its own wastewater treatment plant. 🇺🇸 A historic Gentleman’s Ranch in California is on the market for $8.95M, listed with @villagepropertiesrealestate. ''Palacio del Rio'' is the former hacienda of 'Juan y Lolita Ranchero'. Set in a grove of 100-year old Redwoods and overlooking the Santa Ynez Valley, the Spanish-style property was built in 1929 by Santa Barbara architect Joseph Plunkett for John J. Mitchell Jr. and first wife Lolita Armour. The United Airlines founder built his dream ranch in a bid to recapture some of the romance and spirit of Old California. In 1930, he organized his first “Los Rancheros Visitadores”, a historic horseback trek through the California countryside with 65 friends. The ride was a revival of the hacienda circuit from Old California, a custom of ranchers riding ranch to ranch to help neighbours with the roundup, and ultimately, have a party. Mitchell hosted the event annually, going on to become ‘El Presedente’ of the by-invitation, men’s club, with attendees like Clark Gable, Walt Disney, and Apollo astronaut Wally Shirra. The five-day ride became one of the most exclusive networking events in America, second only to the Bohemian Grove, and gave rise to a theory that Bohemians and Rancheros ruled America in the mid-20th century. The 36.6 acre property is all that remains of the once-12,000 acre ranch estate, later owned by stars Jimmy Stewart and Dean Martin. The sprawling 10,000 square foot hacienda has 6 bedrooms and 6.5 bathrooms, with several reception rooms opening out to the terraces. Two additional guest quarters and a caretaker’s property are spread across the hacienda. With its stunning views over the valley and lush landscape, with a swimming pool and tennis court, the equestrian estate is complete with fenced pastures, a riding ring, and a 4-stall barn. Providing an unparalleled California lifestyle, see more on the blog! .

🇬🇧A Queen Anne country house with spectacular gardens is on the market for £5M, listed with @savills. Originally built in 1739 as a gentleman farm, the Grade II* property has been in the same family since 1850. Set at the end of a long tree-lined drive, tucked behind wisteria-clad gates, the spectacular house is surrounded by incredible gardens, restored and extended over the last 38 years by its owners, passionate gardeners. Frequently used as a backdrop for weddings and photoshoots, they have also hosted open garden days for the National Garden Scheme, allowing the public to explore the various garden rooms on the estate, complete with 2 folies and an arboretum with specimen trees. The Walled Garden dates back to 1739, redesigned in the late 1800s with a box parterre. In the foreground, a yew tower, originally designed as chess pieces, frames the Wild Garden with a grass tennis court. The Pond Garden features a lovely terrace on the former foundations of the dovecot, a perfect spot to observe the deer park.  A herd of 27 Fallow deer was introduced by the owner’s father in 1988, and the family has continued the tradition of a nightly feeding to this day. The 5-bedroom country house features a wealth of period details, with original stone-flagged floors, Delft tile lined fireplaces, bolection-moulded panelling, detailed cornicing, eighteenth century grates, and wooden shutters. Of particular note are the magnificent library and drawing room, added in the 19th century. The library features intricately carved oak panelling rescued from Oxford University's Exeter Chapel; the original pulpit stands in the entrance. The drawing room is illuminated by three 18-pane Georgian sash windows, and features Jacobean paneling and a fantastic fireplace with Flemish carvings. The estate comes with 7 flats and 2 additional cottages.  A spectacular country estate in Oxfordshire, find the listing link on the blog!

🇫🇷 An exceptional stone bastide on the French Riviera is on the market for €9.975M, listed with @carlton.international. With panoramic views over the French Riviera from the Bay of Nice to Madelieu, the hilltop property is within walking distance to the village of Châteauneuf-Grasse, and just 25 minutes to Cannes. Nestled between hills, villages, and golf courses, the stone bastide is set within 2.4 walled acres designed by French landscape architect Jean Mus, with an artificial rock beach by Eric Danton. Terraced gardens with 140 mature olive trees surround the 79-foot infinity swimming pool, with an outdoor BBQ area and exterior WC and shower room. The 6727 square foot bastide has 6 bedrooms, 5 bathrooms, and generous reception rooms with soaring ceilings, French doors, and large windows, featuring remote-controlled electric roller shutters. The neo-Provençal property was built in 2004 by a local architect and features a wealth of custom finishes, like the underfloor heating of the terracotta tile floors and an all-electric eat-in kitchen with a generous pantry. The master suite is an oasis, with his-and-hers dressing rooms and separate bathrooms with a Jacuzzi and designer showers, as well as a Hammam. A finished basement can be converted into a media room and includes an exceptional wine cellar and cigar room. The fully-walled estate comes with 3 secure garages and a 1-bedroom guardian cottage. An incredible lifestyle property on the Cote d’Azur, find the original listing link on the blog!
